# The golden evidence packet must be byte-exact on every platform: its capture
# bodies are hashed and Merkle-committed, and the sealed JSON is canonical
# (LF-only). If Git normalised line endings on checkout, the recomputed hashes
# would diverge and verify_packet would (wrongly) report RED on a fresh clone.
# Treat the whole sealed sample as binary so no EOL conversion ever happens.
samples/real_packet/** -text

# The GATE-2 deterministic-floor demo packet is sealed the same way (canonical
# LF-only JSON over Merkle-committed bodies); EOL conversion would break its
# hashes too. The bodies here are clearly-labelled CONSTRUCTED FIXTURES (not a
# Bright Data capture); the real golden packet is samples/real_packet.
samples/floor_demo_packet/** -text

# The first REAL Bright Data residential DE/BE packet (the GATE-2 LIVE milestone:
# Apple AirPods 4 ANC, identical GTIN across mediamarkt.de/.be). Same sealing —
# canonical LF-only JSON over Merkle-committed raw bodies — so EOL conversion on a
# fresh clone would diverge the recomputed hashes and wrongly report verify_packet
# RED. Treat the whole sealed packet as binary.
samples/live_packet/** -text

# Captured response bodies anywhere are raw bytes — never normalise.
*.body -text

# Committed signer PUBLIC material is exact hex with no trailing CRLF. (The
# PRIVATE key amber/keys/demo-signer.key is gitignored — never committed.)
amber/keys/demo-signer.pub -text
amber/keys/trusted_signers.txt -text
